The patient’s symptoms are indicative of a central herniation, as there is involvement of cranial nerves III, IV, and VI, which are responsible for eye movements. Bilateral uncal herniation can cause pupillary changes, subfalcine herniation can cause leg weakness, and tonsillar herniation can cause respiratory and cardiac irregularities.

Bilateral uncal herniation, subfalcine herniation, and tonsillar herniation can also cause similar symptoms, but they involve different structures within the brain.

Bilateral uncal herniation and subfalcine herniation are less likely to affect the sixth cranial nerve, and tonsillar herniation would present with additional symptoms such as respiratory distress.
